1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. d3 {Very important line, which can arise through 5.d3 move order, when Black responds with 5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5 7.0-0 etc.With this positional approach White avoids heavy theoretical variations , while playing some standard Ryu Lopez/Italian ideas. This is the main reason why this approach has a lot of followers. On the other hand from my personal experience I have to admit that Black play much easier and straightforward to compare with other Ruy Lopez variations , where dark-squared bishop developed to e7. Not surprisingly I have witnessed a lot of examples where Black played Be7-c5 in d3-systems wasting tempo, at the same time believing it's worth it.} d6 {In this chapter I decided to avoid examining White a4-idea , beisdes 9.a4 in the main line, due tot he fact that it will be covered through 7.a4-move order.} 8. c3 {Undoubtfully White main choice, although I would like to mention two alternatives:} ( {In case of} 9. h3 {I don't see the reason to refrain from exchanging White light-squared bishop} Na5 $1 { a good model game here} 10. Nc3 h6 {preventing Bg5 move} 11. Ne2 O-O 12. Ng3 Re8 13. Bd2 Bb6 $5 {interesting approach, Black is not in rush with Nxb3 capture. Usually I trust Michael Adams intuition in Ruy Lopez middlegame!} 14. Qe2 c6 15. c4 {all this happened in Movsesian,S (2635) -Adams, M (2685) Hastings 1996 after natural} Be6 $15 {Black has slightly better game.}  ) ( 9. Be3 O-O {No reason to rush with Bxe3 capture, moreover, Black would be quite happy with Bxc5 dxc5 pawnstructure transformation. Most probably the most challenging move is 9.a4 , but it will be covered through 7.a4 move order. Here we will examine White alternatives} 10. Nbd2 ( 11. c3 Bxe3 12. fxe3 {here I like} Ne7 13. Qe1 Ng6 14. Nh4 {Alonso Alvarez,A (2305) -Delorme,A (2489) Linares 2019 instead of capture on h4 I would prefer} a5 $146 {so after} 15. Nxg6 ( 16. Nf5 d5 {also good for Black.}  ) hxg6 {Black king is more safe with this pawnstructure} 16. Nd2 a4 17. Bd1 Be6 $15 {Black position is very comfortable.}  ) Bxe3 11. fxe3 Na5 $1 {trading knight for White light-squared bishop usually a good idea} 12. Qe1 Nxb3 13. axb3 {two games arrived to this position . I like the following new move} a5 $5 $146 {preventing the idea to fix a6-pawn by means of b3-b4.} 14. Qh4 {now} ( 15. b4 {runs into} a4 $15  ) Bd7 $15  ) h6 {I prefer to avoid if possible} ( O-O 9. Bg5 {the extra possibility together with thematic moves such as 9. Nbd2, 9. Re1 and 9.h3 . I personally had a crazy game after} h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Nxg5 $5 ( 12. Bg3 {definitely the main line}  ) hxg5 12. Bxg5 Kg7 $13 {Gurevich,D (2460) -Avrukh,B (2592) Chicago 2017}  ) 9. Nbd2 {other possibilities:} ( 10. a4 Rb8 11. axb5 {I also examined} ( 12. d4 Bb6 13. Na3 {I still don't get the idea behind White suddenly transposing into main line with d4, while Black has extra move h6, which overall looks like very useful move.However, it's played by Peter Leko and therefore has to be covered} ( {With a black pawn on h6, the idea} 14. a5 $2 {doesn't work, since after} Nxa5 $1 15. Rxa5 Bxa5 16. dxe5 Ng4 { the square h6 is covered , so White cannot play Bg5 as in the line c3, d4.}  ) O-O 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nxb5 Bg4 16. Be3 {we still following Leko play, even though it seems like} ( 17. Bc2 {objectively better move} Qd7 ( d5 $5 {probably enough for equality}  ) 18. dxe5 Bxf3 $1 19. Qxf3 Nxe5 20. Qe2 Bxf2+ 21. Kxf2 Qxb5 22. Qxb5 Rxb5 23. h3 Rfb8 $11 {with blanced position Osipov,A (1708) -Husemann,A (2067) LSS email 2012}  ) ( 17. d5 $2 {help Black tremendously with kingside initiative} Ne7 18. Bc2 {Petrosian, T (2629) -Karthikeyan,P (2426) Al Ain 2008 Black should have played} Qd7 $146 19. c4 Ng6 20. h3 $2 {objectively better} ( 21. Qd3 {but Black has fantastic initiative after} Nh5 $1 $40 { following up by any Nhf4, or f5.}  ) Bxh3 $1 21. gxh3 Qxh3 $19 { White is lost here due to lack of Ng5-move as in the line with c3, d4.}  ) d5 $1 {good timing for th