atives:} ( 17. Bd5 Qe8 { only move, but sufficient enough} 18. h3 ( 19. Qc2 $6 {will be covered through 15. Qc2 move order}  ) Nf6 { I like this move, even though there is nothing wrong with} ( Bf5 19. Re1 Nb4 20. Bc4 d5 21. Bf1 {Giuliani,S (2632) -Karkuth, S (2573) ICCF email 2007 and now the most precise would be} Qd8 $146 22. Qa4 Nc6 {with equal position.}  ) 19. Nxd6 cxd6 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 21. hxg4 Nxg4 {and Black has no problems whatsoever Peled,S-Sen, T Chessfriend. com 2005}  ) ( 17. h3 Bf5 {not dangerous for White} ( Bh5 {since they still have} 18. Bd5  ) 18. Nc3 {played in all four games , where this position happened. Black has several good moves here, but I decided to go with Grischuk solution} h6 $5 { taking control over g5-square, so Black shouldn't worry about Bg5-move} 19. Bd5 Nxc3 20. bxc3 Ne7 21. Bb3 {this position has been occured in Vachier Lagrave,M (2777) -Grischuk,A (2764) Hamburg 2019 I would prefer not to rush with 19...c5 , but to continue with more natural} Ng6 $146 22. Re1 Qf6 {with solid equality.}  ) Na5 $5 {this looks to me more convincing to compare with Qe8} 17. Qxe4 {White tried once} ( 18. Bd5 Bxf3 {in my notes I found another solution} ( Nf6 $146 19. Bg5 c6 $1 {the point with the following illustrative line} 20. Bxc6 Nxc6 21. Qxc6 Bd7 $1 22. Qc4 Bxb5 23. Qxb5 Bxd4 24. Qd3 Bxb2 25. Ra6 {White gets d-pawn with dead equal position.}  ) 19. gxf3 Nf6 20. Bg5 $1 {otherwise White would be worse} h6 21. Bh4 c6 $1 22. Bxc6 Rc8 23. d5 g5 $1 24. Bg3 Nxd5 25. Qd1 Ne3 $5 {interesting try . Black can also play} ( Nxc6 26. Qxd5 Ne7 $1 27. Qxd6 Nf5 { with full compensation.}  ) 26. fxe3 {Potapov,E (1725) -Vasquez Nigro,D (2111) LSS email 2011 I believe Black should have conitnued} Rxc6 $146 27. Nd4 Rc8 {with complex game. Certainly very important to emphasize that dangerous looking} 28. Nf5 {well met by} Nc4 29. Nxh6+ Kh7 30. Ng4 f5 31. b3 Nxe3 32. Nxe3 Bxe3+ $11  ) Bxf3 18. Qxf3 ( {Nobody tried} 19. Bxf7+ Rxf7 20. gxf3 c6 21. b4 { best for White. Wor